name: dibenzofuran, 1,3,6,8-tetrachloro-
Reason: The basic structure for the comparison is benzene, which has a melting point of 5.5°C. Dibenzofuran has two benzene rings fused to a central furan ring, significantly increasing the rigidity of the molecule, which would typically raise the melting point considerably due to the increased symmetry and planarity. Each chlorine substituent adds to the molecular weight and, due to its electronegativity, also introduces dipole-dipole interactions, which further increase intermolecular forces. Four chlorine atoms would thus have a cumulative effect. Based on similar chlorinated aromatic compounds, each chlorine might be estimated to add roughly 20-30°C to the melting point of the parent structure. However, dibenzofuran also has a heteroatom (oxygen) in the central ring, contributing to the possibility of hydrogen bonding and enhancing dipole-dipole interactions, which might contribute another significant increase to the melting point.
